ber 1427":"omkring 1353–20. september 1427","1353–1427":"1353–1427","1340–1390":"1340–1390","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1387–1434":"1387–1434","1321–1359":"1321–1359","1337–Female":"1337–Afdød","Aft 1359":"efter 1359","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1434":"1434","Abt 1353":"omkring 1353","1387":"1387","20 September 1427":"20. september 1427","1321":"1321","1353":"1353","6 August 1417":"6. august 1417","Bef 1390":"før 1390","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1427":"1427","Yorkshire, England":"Jórvík, England","Leybourne, Kentshire, England":"Leybourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Carleton, Yorkshire, England":"Carleton, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"Abt 1353–20 September 1427":"circa 1353–20 september 1427","1353–1427":"1353–1427","1340–1390":"1340–1390","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1387–1434":"1387–1434","1321–1359":"1321–1359","1337–Female":"1337–Overleden","Aft 1359":"na 1359","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1434":"1434","Abt 1353":"circa 1353","1387":"1387","20 September 1427":"20 september 1427","1321":"1321","1353":"1353","6 August 1417":"6 augustus 1417","Bef 1390":"vóór 1390","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1427":"1427","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Leybourne, Kentshire, England":"Leybourne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Carleton, Yorkshire, England":"Carleton, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1353–20 September 1427":"about 1353–20 September 1427","1353–1427":"1353–1427","1340–1390":"1340–1390","1360–1417":"1360–1417","1380–1429":"1380–1429","1387–1434":"1387–1434","1321–1359":"1321–1359","1337–Female":"1337–Deceased","Aft 1359":"after 1359","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1337":"1337","1359":"1359","1434":"1434","Abt 1353":"about 1353","1387":"1387","20 September 1427":"20 September 1427","1321":"1321","1353":"1353","6 August 1417":"6 August 1417","Bef 1390":"before 1390","1429":"1429","1417":"1417","1427":"1427","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Leybourne, Kentshire, England":"Leybourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Carleton, Yorkshire, England":"Carleton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scrope","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman: of uncertain origin. Tengvik suggests derivation from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Skrópi</i> (of doubtful etymology, but compare Old Scandinavian  <i>skrópa-maðr</i> ‘hypocrite’, containing the genitive plural form of  <i>skrópar</i> ‘sham, hypocrisy’). It is possible, but not certain, that this personal name forms the first element of the Notts place-name Scrooby. Otherwise there is no evidence for its currency in England or, more relevantly, in Normandy. Richards Castle (in Herefs and Shrops) was apparently named after Richard Scrope, who held estates in Herefs and Worcs in 1066 and was a Norman favourite of Edward the Confessor. The Scrope family, whose name is traditionally pronounced /skru:p/, was politically important in medieval England, and acquired estates in Lincs (Barton on Humber), NR Yorks (Castle Bolton), and in ER Yorks (Flotmanby). Richard (le) Scrope of Bolton, in Wensleydale, was Lord Chancellor in the reign of Richard II. The use of  <i>le</i> and  <i>de</i> in the surname, suggesting either a nickname or a locative name, must be treated with caution because these were often added gratuitously to Anglo-Norman surnames as a sign of high social status."],"variants":[{"name":"Scroop","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]},{"name":"Scroope","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Scrope  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":29,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],